            AppRoutes = """["/planning"]""",
            Tags = """["planning","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## When Planning Is Turned Off, and Empty States\n\nPlanning Cycles have to be turned on for your site. When planning is turned off, the whole area is hidden — the page and its sidebar link disappear, so nobody reaches it by normal navigation. The dashboard's cycle-progress card handles this quietly too: instead of an error, it simply shows its \"no active cycle\" message.\n\nThat's different from the empty states you see when planning is turned **on** but there's just no data yet:\n- The right side shows \"No cycle selected\" with a \"Create first cycle\" button.\n- A cycle with no jobs shows \"No jobs committed\".\n- A backlog with nothing available shows \"No available jobs\".\n\nThese are normal, data-is-empty messages — not the hidden-when-turned-off case above.\n\n## Who Can Do What\n\nAccess splits into two levels: **viewing** (open to most roles) and **changing** (managers only).\n\n| Action | Who can do it |\n|--------|---------------|\n| See the list of cycles | Admin, Manager, PM, Engineer, Production Worker |\n| See the current cycle | Admin, Manager, PM, Engineer, Production Worker |\n| Open a cycle's details | Admin, Manager, PM, Engineer, Production Worker |\n| Create a cycle | Admin, Manager |\n| Edit a cycle | Admin, Manager |\n| Activate a cycle | Admin, Manager |\n| Complete or roll over a cycle | Admin, Manager |\n| Add a job | Admin, Manager |\n| Remove a job | Admin, Manager |\n| Reorder jobs | Admin, Manager |\n| Mark a job done | Admin, Manager |\n\nAnyone with view-only access — a PM, Engineer, or Production Worker — who tries a change (including the plus button, drag-to-add, or a per-job complete) is turned away. The buttons aren't hidden for those roles, so the block happens the moment they try. Planning is a manager-run activity the whole shop can watch in real time.\n\n## What the Form Checks When You Create a Cycle\n\n- **Name** — required; can't be blank. You can type up to 100 characters.\n- **Start date** — required.\n- **End date** — required, and it must fall after the start date. The same day is not allowed. If it isn't after the start, you'll see \"End date must be after start date.\"\n- **Goals** — optional; a few paragraphs at most.\n- **Cycle length** — worked out for you from the two dates. When a cycle rolls over, the next one keeps the same length.\n\nEvery new cycle is saved in Planning status no matter what — you can't set the status when creating one. Editing a cycle changes only its name, dates, and goals; the status changes only through Activate and Complete. If something doesn't pass these checks, the cycle isn't saved and you're told what to fix.\n\n## How the Dashboard Picks the \"Current\" Cycle\n\nThe dashboard chooses the current cycle for you — it isn't a setting you pick. It looks at every cycle that isn't Completed (so both Planning and Active cycles count), then picks the one with the most recent start date. If there are no un-completed cycles, the dashboard card shows its empty state with a link into planning.\n\nThe card works out the done count, the percentage complete, and the days remaining from that cycle's jobs, and it flags the cycle as overdue when the end date has already passed — even if the cycle is still in Planning.\n\nBecause it goes by the most recent start date, creating a new cycle with a later start date makes it the dashboard's current cycle right away, even while an older Active cycle is still open.\n","sections":[]}"""
        });

        Log.Information("Seeded Planning Cycles training modules");
    }
}
